<DOC><DOCNO> AP880318-0159 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 1545EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Burma-Riot     03-18 0212</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Burma-Riot,0220</SECOND><HEAD>Students Riot in Burma in Cassette Tape Dispute</HEAD><DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Anti-government protesters set fire to adowntown department store Friday as demonstrations over the playingof music in a tea shop persisted in the capital.   Hundreds of students and other protester demonstrated in supportof students at the Rangoon Institute of Technology who rioted March12 after a dispute in a tea shop.   One student died in the violence, which began when studentsargued with villagers over what songs to play on a tape player.   Police occupied the campus Tuesday and detained a number ofstudents suspected of fighting the villagers.   Larger groups of both students and villagers resumed fighting onSunday and about 200 students set fire to seven buildings,according to the Burma Broadcasting Service.   On Friday, witnesses said more than 300 students from governmenthigh schools gathered at a public park.   They shouted anti-government slogans, and joined by outsiders,wrecked government cars in the area. The protesters then set fireto a nearby government department store. Traffic was paralyzed.   Several arrests were made before riot police dispersed the crowdthree hours after the protest began.   Student disturbances are rare in this southeast Asian nation,which has been under Ne Win's one-party rule since 1962.</TEXT></DOC>